what it returns. REJECTION-GATE: Nothing in the behavior text disqualifies Agentic — there is no deterministic routing or parsing step here; the failure lives in whether the model's generation is on-topic, which only a real model can reveal.","test_description":"Submit a specific, non-generic customer question (e.g., 'How do I reset my two-factor authentication?') along with a realistic conversation history to the live chatbot pipeline. Call the real LLM endpoint. Assert that the returned response contains topic-relevant content (e.g., references to authentication or account security) and does not consist solely of generic filler phrases. Run several times to capture non-determinism.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.85,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Tone re-check correctly identifies when a response is too formal for a casual-tier customer and triggers regeneration","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: The behavior tests 'correctly identifies' — i.e., classification accuracy of the tone-checker. In a modern chatbot system, tone classification is itself an LLM call (the problem describes a 'tone-checking step' that 're-prompts the LLM'). A stub tone-checker trivially returns whatever value the test author pre-programs, so it cannot catch misclassifications from the real model. Running with a real LLM may yield inconsistent classifications across runs. MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing the tone-checker means the test never exercises whether the real model actually recognizes formal register. REJECTION-GATE: The behavior text does not describe a deterministic rule-based classifier (no mention of keyword lists or regex); absent disqualifying evidence, Agentic is retained.","test_description":"Construct a response using high-formality markers (honorifics, passive voice, complex sentence structure, deferential phrasing). Pass it through the real tone-check step with customer_tier=casual using a live LLM call. Assert that the tone-check flags the response as too formal and returns a regeneration trigger. Repeat with a clearly casual response and assert no regeneration is triggered.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Full exchange (user message, generated response, any regenerations) is persisted to database with correct timestamps","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure lives at the boundary between the service layer and the persistence layer — wrong field mapping, missing regeneration records, or timestamp truncation only surface when both modules are wired together. A unit test of the service in isolation cannot catch a persistence bug. REAL-INFRA: An in-process fake/in-memory database is sufficient; the failure mode (missing records, wrong field values, incorrect timestamps) does not require a real remote DB or OS-level I/O. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real OS/network required — in-memory DB catches schema and field-mapping bugs. (b) LLM output can be fully stubbed; what matters is that the service correctly writes whatever it received. (c) No chained agentic steps.","test_description":"Wire the chatbot service to an in-memory database. Stub the LLM to return a known initial response and a known regenerated response (simulating a tone-check retry). Invoke the full pipeline. Query the in-memory DB and assert: one exchange record exists; it contains the user message, the final response, and the regenerated draft; timestamps are present, non-null, and monotonically ordered (user message ≤ first generation ≤ regeneration).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.14,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When tone check triggers regeneration, the second response replaces the first — the customer never sees the rejected draft","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is a routing/state bug at the boundary between the tone-check module and the response-dispatch module — the wrong object propagates to the caller. This only surfaces when both modules are wired together. REAL-INFRA: The replacement logic is deterministic; we can fully control the scenario by stubbing the LLM (first call returns formal text, second returns acceptable text) and stubbing or configuring the tone-checker to flag the first. No real LLM needed to catch a state-management bug. MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing the LLM here does NOT hide the failure — the failure is that the service routes the wrong response object to the customer, and a stub gives full control to produce the triggering scenario. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real OS/network. (b) Correctness of replacement is deterministic — we are not testing LLM quality, only which object propagates. (c) No chained agentic steps.","test_description":"Configure a stub LLM: first invocation returns a formally-worded response; second invocation returns a casual-appropriate response. Configure the tone-checker (or use a real one with a crafted formal input) to flag the first response as too formal. Invoke the pipeline end-to-end. Assert that (1) the value returned to the caller equals the second (regenerated) response, not the first; and (2) the first rejected draft does not appear anywhere in the object returned to the caller.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.13,"Workflow":0.04}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10023,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10023},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_ge